At low wavevector $q$, the linear dispersion relation $\omega=c_{s}q$, where $c_{s}$ is the speed of sound, is visible for all values of connectivity $Z$, except for the marginally-stable isostatic states with $Z=6$ which has $G=0$, and therefore cannot support elastic waves. At the crossover, 
$q=q^{*}$, the dispersion relation starts to deviate from linear and crosses over into an approximately parabolic regime, characterized by the scaling $\omega\sim Dq^{2}$. Here $D$ is a diffusion coefficient for mode-diffusion due to scattering events caused by the local inversion-symmetry breaking.
This fact is used in the main text to derive the scaling $\omega_{BP}\sim G \sim (Z-6)$.  




